nge each other's ideas on the nature of post-foundationalist critique. At the core of the argument lies the timely question of the role that each person can play in creating a truly humane society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh1 aCaputo, John D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCaputo, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarsh, James L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNys, Martin J. De, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWestphal, Merold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYount, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311074329640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329611840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823296118423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823296118/original  a978-3-11-074329-6  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK